## 🗂️ Category 9: File Masquerading / Content Spoofing Tests

> What happens when someone renames an unrelated file (.pdf, .jpg, .xlsx, .csv, .zip) and uploads it with an MRX/ACK/RESP filename.

> **Key Design Fact:** The backend uses **content fingerprinting**, NOT filename.
> [detectSchema()](file:///d:/Antigravity/AntiGravity_Kit/magellen-responce/backend/src/main/java/com/mrx/fileparserengine/service/UnifiedParserService.java#874-915) checks: line length + first char + magic bytes (cols 2-26).
> The filename (`fileNameHint`) is used **only for logging** — never for routing.

### MASK-01 · PDF Renamed as MRX File

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** A real PDF file renamed to `MRX_TEST.BCBSMN_PRIME_CLAIMS.txt`
- **Why It Matters:** PDF header starts with `%PDF-`, binary content, short/irregular lines
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "INVALID"` — PDF header does NOT match 921-char `H` + `BCBSMN`
  - `lines` is empty · frontend shows "Unrecognized File Format"
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `security`, `file-spoofing`

### MASK-02 · DOCX/XLSX Renamed as MRX File

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** A `.docx` or `.xlsx` file renamed to `MRX_TEST.txt`
- **Why It Matters:** Office files are ZIP archives. Binary content, no textual first line ≥ 900 chars
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "INVALID"`
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `security`

### MASK-03 · Image (JPG/PNG) Renamed as RESP File

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** A `.jpg` image renamed to `TEST.PRIME_BCBSMN_GEN_CLAIMS_RESP.txt`
- **Why It Matters:** JPEG starts with `FF D8 FF` magic bytes. First char is NOT 'H'
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "INVALID"`
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `security`

### MASK-04 · Plain CSV File Uploaded as ACK

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** A normal CSV file (`Name,Age,Value\n...`) renamed to `TEST.MCMSMN_CLAIMS_ACK.txt`
- **Why It Matters:** CSV lines are short (< 50 chars), won't match 220-char ACK requirement
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "INVALID"`
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `edge-case`

### MASK-05 · ACK File Uploaded to MRX Convert Endpoint

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/convert/mrx-to-ack`
- **Input:** A valid ACK file uploaded (wrong type for this endpoint)
- **Why It Matters:** Convert endpoint calls [parseFile()](file:///d:/Antigravity/AntiGravity_Kit/magellen-responce/backend/src/main/java/com/mrx/fileparserengine/controller/UnifiedParserController.java#66-115) internally. ACK content won't parse as MRX.
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK` (endpoint succeeds)
  - `content` has 0 data records (nothing to convert — no MRX data lines)
  - OR graceful empty ACK with just Header + Trailer
  - Does NOT crash with 500
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `wrong-file-type`, `functional`

### MASK-06 · RESP File Uploaded to MRX-to-RESP Endpoint

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/convert/mrx-to-resp`
- **Input:** A valid RESP file uploaded instead of MRX
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - Detected as RESP (not MRX), `dataLines` list will be empty (no MRX data to convert)
  - Response `content` has Header + 0 data lines + Trailer
  - Does NOT throw NullPointerException
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `wrong-file-type`

### MASK-07 · Crafted Text File That Passes MRX Content Fingerprint

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** A hand-crafted text file where:
  - First line is exactly 921 characters
  - Starts with `H`
  - Cols 2–26 = `BCBSMN` (padded)
  - But data lines are NOT real MRX structure
- **Why It Matters:** This is the most sophisticated spoofing attempt — bypasses filename check AND line-length fingerprint
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "MRX"` ← **WILL be detected as MRX** (this is expected behavior)
  - BUT: data lines will have `isValid: false` and field errors everywhere
  - `validationErrors` will contain "Trailer Record Count Mismatch" or "Missing Trailer record"
  - The file is **not silently accepted** — validation errors surface all anomalies
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `security`, `crafted-input`, `⚠️ documents-known-behavior`

### MASK-08 · Empty File with MRX Filename

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** 0-byte file named `MRX_TEST.BCBSMN_PRIME_CLAIMS.txt`
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK`
  - `detectedSchema: "INVALID"` — `content.isEmpty()` → immediate return
  - `lines` is empty
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `edge-case`

### MASK-09 · Null Byte / Unicode in Filename (Filename Injection)

- **Endpoint:** `POST /api/parse`
- **Input:** Valid MRX content with a filename containing `null bytes`, unicode, or `../path` traversal sequences
  - e.g., `filename="../../etc/passwd.txt"`
- **Why It Matters:** `fileNameHint` is used in logging. Check it doesn't leak to response or cause path traversal.
- **Expected:**
  - `200 OK` — content is valid MRX, parses normally
  - `detectedSchema: "MRX"`
  - The malicious filename does NOT appear in the response body
  - Server logs may contain it (logging is OK) but response is clean
- **Tags:** `masquerade`, `security`, `path-traversal`, `filename-injection`

---

> ### 💡 Summary: What the Backend Does Right
>
> - ✅ **Content fingerprinting** — filename is never used for routing
> - ✅ **Strict line length check** — binary files with short/irregular lines → INVALID
> - ✅ **Magic byte check** — `BCBSMN` / `PRIME` at exact column positions
> - ⚠️ **Crafted files (MASK-07)** — CAN pass schema detection but will fail field-level validation
> - ✅ **Filename injection (MASK-09)** — `fileNameHint` flows only to logging, not response

